1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,360
 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture

2
00:00:02,360 --> 00:00:05,120
 on object-oriented programming in JavaScript.

3
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:09,620
 I teach object-oriented programming in Python,

4
00:00:09,620 --> 00:00:12,340
 in PHP, and in JavaScript.

5
00:00:12,340 --> 00:00:15,440
 And I use the same slides over and over and over again,

6
00:00:15,440 --> 00:00:19,840
 and that's because object-oriented concepts are the same.

7
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:21,980
 So if you've taken other classes from me,

8
00:00:21,980 --> 00:00:23,880
 you've seen some of these slides.

9
00:00:23,880 --> 00:00:25,340
 They're adapted a little bit from JavaScript,

10
00:00:25,340 --> 00:00:27,240
 'cause JavaScript's object-oriented pattern

11
00:00:27,240 --> 00:00:29,980
 is particularly awesome, right?

12
00:00:29,980 --> 00:00:32,200
 But there's this concept of a class,

13
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:34,040
 which is like a template.

14
00:00:34,040 --> 00:00:38,020
 There's a concept of code and data in a class,

15
00:00:38,020 --> 00:00:40,400
 whether you call the code method or message is up to you,

16
00:00:40,400 --> 00:00:43,320
 whether you call the data attributes or fields.

17
00:00:43,320 --> 00:00:45,400
 And then an object is an instance of the class.

18
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:47,400
 And so the cookie cutter is,

19
00:00:47,400 --> 00:00:49,920
 the cookie cutter is the shape that's the class,

20
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:52,680
 and the cookie itself that can be specialized,

21
00:00:52,680 --> 00:00:54,160
 and it's an instance.

22
00:00:54,160 --> 00:00:56,600
 Millions of cookies come from one cookie cutter,

23
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:58,560
 and that's object-oriented.

24
00:00:58,560 --> 00:01:01,120
 And so the key is, is the craft of it

25
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:02,960
 is building the cookie cutter

26
00:01:02,960 --> 00:01:06,360
 so that it makes awesome cookies.

27
00:01:06,360 --> 00:01:09,880
 So the class, like I said, is the template,

28
00:01:09,880 --> 00:01:12,360
 it's a blueprint, it's not the actual thing,

29
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:15,200
 but it is the precise instructions

30
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:16,800
 on how to make the thing.

31
00:01:16,800 --> 00:01:19,760
 An instance is once you make the cookie,

32
00:01:19,760 --> 00:01:21,360
 you can have different frosting on it,

33
00:01:21,360 --> 00:01:23,640
 you can have all kinds of other things.

34
00:01:23,640 --> 00:01:26,140
 You can make subclasses,

35
00:01:26,140 --> 00:01:27,520
 which is what we do for inheritance,

36
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:31,040
 which makes specialized versions of the class.

37
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:33,360
 Now, the methods are the code.

38
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,460
 So in classic programming,

39
00:01:35,460 --> 00:01:37,720
 we think of like code and data structures,

40
00:01:37,720 --> 00:01:39,640
 the algorithms and data structures.

41
00:01:39,640 --> 00:01:41,200
 Data structures are the shape of data,

42
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:43,320
 and algorithms are the shape of the code,

43
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:45,820
 the way the code is made to work.

44
00:01:45,820 --> 00:01:47,800
 The methods are the algorithms

45
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:50,720
 that make up the code part of every object.

46
00:01:50,720 --> 00:01:52,640
 Every object has code and data,

47
00:01:52,640 --> 00:01:54,720
 and often the code works on the data

48
00:01:54,720 --> 00:01:56,960
 that's inside the object.

49
00:01:56,960 --> 00:01:59,800
 Some object-oriented sort of schools of thought

50
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:03,520
 use method, and some use message.

51
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:06,120
 The more purist folks tend to use messages,

52
00:02:06,120 --> 00:02:08,340
 like you're sending a message, here's the object,

53
00:02:08,340 --> 00:02:11,580
 not the class, you're sending a message to the object.

54
00:02:11,580 --> 00:02:13,400
 I tend to use method,

55
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:15,340
 'cause method is a bit of code that lives in there,

56
00:02:15,340 --> 00:02:17,000
 and that's just 'cause I think of things

57
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:21,380
 from like Fortran or C, very procedural way of thinking.

58
00:02:21,380 --> 00:02:25,060
 So objects in JavaScript are a little different,

59
00:02:25,060 --> 00:02:27,560
 and if you've seen me talk about objects in Python,

60
00:02:27,560 --> 00:02:32,120
 or objects in PHP, or even objects in Java,

61
00:02:32,120 --> 00:02:34,680
 which I taught a lot a long time ago,

62
00:02:34,680 --> 00:02:37,200
 or C++, they're very different.

63
00:02:37,200 --> 00:02:38,840
 And the key thing is,

64
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:40,800
 it certainly is a storing reuse pattern.

65
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:44,160
 It is a mechanism to create data and code

66
00:02:44,160 --> 00:02:47,040
 and put it into one kind of reusable thing.

67
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:50,000
 But the key thing is, is that the function keyword

68
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:54,280
 is actually, in a sense, an executable statement,

69
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:58,080
 and you can take and use the function keyword,

70
00:02:58,080 --> 00:03:02,120
 and the function is, in a sense, calling a function

71
00:03:02,120 --> 00:03:04,840
 that causes code to come back to you.

72
00:03:04,840 --> 00:03:08,320
 So you can have the function create code

73
00:03:08,320 --> 00:03:10,960
 and then assign it into the variable.

74
00:03:10,960 --> 00:03:12,920
 These are called first-class functions,

75
00:03:12,920 --> 00:03:14,320
 and it has to do with the fact

76
00:03:14,320 --> 00:03:16,400
 that in first-class functions,

77
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:19,840
 you have this symmetry between code and data.

78
00:03:19,840 --> 00:03:21,360
 The code is just data.

79
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:25,000
 And of all of the modern programming languages,

80
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,560
 Lisp really was the original code-data kind of duality.

81
00:03:29,560 --> 00:03:32,580
 JavaScript is very, very, very much throwback

82
00:03:32,580 --> 00:03:37,200
 to the Lisp tradition of data and code look the same way,

83
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:39,480
 or can be treated the same way.

84
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:41,120
 You can have X as a variable,

85
00:03:41,120 --> 00:03:43,080
 and you can assign it to be 42.

86
00:03:43,080 --> 00:03:44,120
 You can have it be a string,

87
00:03:44,120 --> 00:03:45,560
 or you can have it be a function

88
00:03:45,560 --> 00:03:47,120
 that adds two numbers together.

89
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:50,760
 And it's just X, and that is kind of elegant.

90
00:03:50,760 --> 00:03:52,760
 So that's called first-class functions,

91
00:03:52,760 --> 00:03:56,040
 and that functions themselves are the code.

92
00:03:56,040 --> 00:04:00,080
 The code in systems is manipulable as data.

93
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:03,500
 Copy around, use it, reuse it, et cetera.

94
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:06,240
 So up next, we're gonna take a look

95
00:04:06,240 --> 00:04:10,620
 at how we put together a sample class in JavaScript.

96
00:04:10,620 --> 00:04:13,200
 (upbeat music)

